## 4\. Detailed Implementation Phases

### Phase 1: Block Generation (With "API Pull" & "Granular Tracking")

**Context:** We need to create blocks for 400 members. Passing IDs in the event is forbidden (size limit).

#### Step 1: Orchestrator (Pull & Init)

The Orchestrator receives the command, fetches IDs via Internal API, and initializes the "Checklist" in DB.

```java
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class BlockOrchestrator {

    private final MemberModuleApi memberApi; // Internal API
    private final ProcessStatusRepository statusRepo;
    private final BlockAsyncWorker asyncWorker;

    @ApplicationModuleListener
    @Transactional
    public void on(GenerateBlocksCommand command) {
        String reviewId = command.reviewId();

        // 1. PULL: Fetch all IDs via Interface (Bypass Event limit)
        List<String> allMemberIds = memberApi.getAllMemberIds(reviewId);

        // 2. INIT: Create "TO_DO" rows for traceability
        // This ensures we know exactly what needs to be done.
        statusRepo.initBatch(reviewId, allMemberIds, ProcessStatus.TO_DO);

        // 3. DISPATCH: Send to workers
        dispatchPending(reviewId);
    }
    
    public void dispatchPending(String reviewId) {
        // Fetch TO_DO or ERROR rows
        var pending = statusRepo.findPending(reviewId);
        pending.forEach(p -> asyncWorker.process(reviewId, p.getMemberId()));
    }
}
```

#### Step 2: Async Worker (The Execution)

Processes one member. Updates status to SUCCESS or ERROR.

```java
@Service
public class BlockAsyncWorker {

    @Async("workerExecutor") // Custom Thread Pool (Size 50)
    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
    public void process(String reviewId, String memberId) {
        var status = statusRepo.findByKey(reviewId, memberId);
        
        try {
            // A. Update State -> PROCESSING
            status.setStatus(ProcessStatus.PROCESSING);
            statusRepo.save(status);

            // B. Logic: Call Ext API & Create Blocks
            var data = externalClient.fetch(memberId); // Retryable client
            blockService.createBlocks(data, reviewId);

            // C. Update State -> SUCCESS
            status.setStatus(ProcessStatus.SUCCESS);
            statusRepo.save(status);

        } catch (Exception e) {
            // D. Handle Error
            status.setStatus(ProcessStatus.ERROR);
            status.setErrorMessage(e.getMessage());
            statusRepo.save(status);
        } finally {
            // E. Notify Saga to check if ALL threads are done
            events.publishEvent(new MemberProcessingAttemptFinished(reviewId));
        }
    }
}
```

### Phase 2: Saga Error Handling & Retry Logic

**Context:** What happens when the Workers finish, but 5 members failed?

```java
@Component
public class SagaManager {

    @ApplicationModuleListener
    @Transactional
    public void on(MemberProcessingAttemptFinished event) {
        // 1. Check if all workers are done (No rows in 'PROCESSING')
        if (statusRepo.countByStatus(PROCESSING) > 0) return;

        // 2. Check for Errors
        long errorCount = statusRepo.countByStatus(ERROR);
        var saga = sagaRepo.findById(event.reviewId());

        if (errorCount == 0) {
            // SUCCESS: Move to Salesforce Sync
            saga.setStep(SagaStep.SYNC_MEMBERS);
            triggerSync(saga);
        } 
        else if (saga.getGenerationRetryCount() < ReviewSaga.MAX_RETRIES) {
            // RETRY STRATEGY: Re-dispatch only failed items
            saga.setGenerationRetryCount(saga.getGenerationRetryCount() + 1);
            sagaRepo.save(saga);
            
            // Re-trigger Orchestrator to pick up ERROR rows
            blockOrchestrator.dispatchPending(saga.getReviewId());
        } 
        else {
            // FAILURE / PARTIAL SUCCESS STRATEGY
            // Option A: Stop -> Human Intervention
            // Option B: Continue -> Sync only successful items (Chosen here)
            log.warn("Review {} proceeding with {} errors", saga.getReviewId(), errorCount);
            saga.setStep(SagaStep.SYNC_MEMBERS);
            triggerSync(saga);
        }
    }
}
```

### Phase 3: Salesforce Sync (Re-entrant Loop)

**Context:** Sync 2000 items in batches of 200. Resume on crash.

```java
@Component
public class SalesforceSyncOrchestrator {

    @ApplicationModuleListener
    @Transactional
    public void on(SyncBatchCompletedEvent event) {
        var saga = sagaRepo.findById(event.reviewId());

        // 1. Update Cursor
        if (event.isMember()) saga.setSfMemberOffset(saga.getSfMemberOffset() + event.count());
        else saga.setSfBlockOffset(saga.getSfBlockOffset() + event.count());

        // 2. Loop Logic
        if (saga.getSfMemberOffset() < saga.getTotalMembers()) {
             // Sync Next 200 Members
             commandGateway.dispatch(new SyncMembersCommand(saga.getReviewId(), saga.getSfMemberOffset()));
        } 
        else if (saga.getSfBlockOffset() < saga.getTotalBlocks()) {
             // Sync Next 200 Blocks
             commandGateway.dispatch(new SyncBlocksCommand(saga.getReviewId(), saga.getSfBlockOffset()));
        } 
        else {
             // FINISHED
             saga.setStep(SagaStep.FINALIZING);
             finalizeReview(saga);
        }
        
        sagaRepo.save(saga);
    }
}
```

